            "content": "# ChainProvider Test Coverage Improvement Plan\n\n> **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:subagent-driven-development (recommended) or superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task. Steps use checkbox (`- [ ]`) syntax for tracking.\n\n**Goal:** Improve test coverage for all modules that use `ChainProvider` / JSON-RPC provider, targeting the untested pure-logic functions first, then async functions testable via `MockChainProvider`.\n\n**Architecture:** Enhance `MockChainProvider` to support block-by-number lookups and error simulation, then add tests bottom-up: pure functions first, then async functions that exercise the mock. All tests go in the existing `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` blocks within each file.\n\n**Tech Stack:** Rust, tokio, alloy, lru, cargo-llvm-cov + cargo-nextest\n\n---\n\n## Current Coverage Baseline (relevant files)\n\n| File | Line Coverage |\n|------|-------------|\n| `provider.rs` | 13.85% |\n| `indexer/fetch_logs.rs` | 16.17% |\n| `indexer/native_transfer.rs` | 22.36% |\n| `indexer/start.rs` | 31.24% |\n| `indexer/reorg.rs` | 37.04% |\n| `blockclock/mod.rs` | (via fetcher) |\n\n---\n\n### Task 1: Enhance MockChainProvider for block-by-number lookups\n\nThe current `MockChainProvider::get_block_by_number_batch` ignores the requested block numbers and returns ALL stored blocks. This prevents testing `find_fork_point` and `spawn_post_confirmation_verifier` which rely on fetching specific blocks by number. We need the mock to filter its stored blocks by the requested numbers.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `core/src/provider.rs` (lines 1014-1019 in the `MockChainProvider` impl)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\nAdd to the existing `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` block at the bottom of `core/src/provider.rs`:\n\n```rust\n#[tokio::test]\nasync fn mock_chain_provider_filters_blocks_by_number() {\n    use alloy::consensus::Header;\n    use alloy::rpc::types::Block;\n\n    let block_100 = AnyRpcBlock::from(Block {\n        header: Header { number: 100, ..Default::default() }.seal_slow(),\n        ..Default::default()\n    });\n    let block_200 = AnyRpcBlock::from(Block {\n        header: Header { number: 200, ..Default::default() }.seal_slow(),\n        ..Default::default()\n    });\n    let mock = MockChainProvider::new(1).with_blocks(vec![block_100, block_200]);\n    let result = mock\n        .get_block_by_number_batch(&[U64::from(100)], false)\n        .await\n        .unwrap();\n    assert_eq!(result.len(), 1);\n    assert_eq!(result[0].header.number, 100);\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `cargo nextest run -p rindexer mock_chain_provider_filters_blocks_by_number`\nExpected: FAIL — currently returns both blocks (2) instead of 1.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Fix MockChainProvider::get_block_by_number_batch to filter by requested numbers**\n\nIn the `impl ChainProvider for MockChainProvider` block, change `get_block_by_number_batch`:\n\n```rust\nasync fn get_block_by_number_batch(\n    &self,\n    block_numbers: &[U64],\n    _include_txs: bool,\n) -> Result<Vec<AnyRpcBlock>, ProviderError> {\n    let requested: std::collections::HashSet<u64> =\n        block_numbers.iter().map(|n| n.to::<u64>()).collect();\n    Ok(self\n        .blocks\n        .iter()\n        .filter(|b| requested.contains(&b.header.number))\n        .map(|b| (**b).clone())\n        .collect())\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `cargo nextest run -p rindexer mock_chain_provider_filters_blocks_by_number`\nExpected: PASS\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add core/src/provider.rs\ngit commit -m \"fix: MockChainProvider filters blocks by requested numbers\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### Task 2: Add `with_max_block_range` builder to MockChainProvider\n\nCurrently there is no way to set `max_block_range` on the mock. Several tests (fetch_logs historic) rely on this.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `core/src/provider.rs` (MockChainProvider impl block, ~line 963)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\n```rust\n#[test]\nfn mock_chain_provider_with_max_block_range() {\n    let mock = MockChainProvider::new(1).with_max_block_range(500);\n    assert_eq!(mock.max_block_range(), Some(U64::from(500)));\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `cargo nextest run -p rindexer mock_chain_provider_with_max_block_range`\nExpected: FAIL — method does not exist yet.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Add the builder method**\n\nAdd to the `impl MockChainProvider` block after `with_traces`:\n\n```rust\npub fn with_max_block_range(mut self, n: u64) -> Self {\n    self.max_block_range = Some(U64::from(n));\n    self\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `cargo nextest run -p rindexer mock_chain_provider_with_max_block_range`\nExpected: PASS\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add core/src/provider.rs\ngit commit -m \"feat: add with_max_block_range builder to MockChainProvider\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### Task 3: Test `is_known_zk_evm_compatible_chain`\n\nPure function at `core/src/provider.rs:194`. Currently 0% coverage. No dependencies.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `core/src/provider.rs` (add tests to existing test module)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write tests**\n\n```rust\n#[test]\nfn known_zk_chains_return_true() {\n    // ZkSync\n    assert_eq!(is_known_zk_evm_compatible_chain(Chain::from_named(NamedChain::ZkSync)), Some(true));\n    // Scroll\n    assert_eq!(is_known_zk_evm_compatible_chain(Chain::from_named(NamedChain::Scroll)), Some(true));\n    // Linea\n    assert_eq!(is_known_zk_evm_compatible_chain(Chain::from_named(NamedChain::Linea)), Some(true));\n}\n\n#[test]\nfn known_non_zk_chains_return_false() {\n    assert_eq!(\n        is_known_zk_evm_compatible_chain(Chain::from_named(NamedChain::Mainnet)),\n        Some(false)\n    );\n    assert_eq!(\n        is_known_zk_evm_compatible_chain(Chain::from_named(NamedChain::Arbitrum)),\n        Some(false)\n    );\n    assert_eq!(\n        is_known_zk_evm_compatible_chain(Chain::from_named(NamedChain::Base)),\n        Some(false)\n    );\n    assert_eq!(\n        is_known_zk_evm_compatible_chain(Chain::from_named(NamedChain::Polygon)),\n        Some(false)\n    );\n}\n\n#[test]\nfn unknown_chain_id_returns_none() {\n    // A chain ID not in any match arm\n    let unknown = Chain::from_id(999999);\n    assert_eq!(is_known_zk_evm_compatible_chain(unknown), None);\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run tests**\n\nRun: `cargo nextest run -p rindexer known_zk_chains`\nExpected: PASS (these are pure tests against existing code)\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add core/src/provider.rs\ngit commit -m \"test: cover is_known_zk_evm_compatible_chain\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### Task 4: Test `find_fork_point`\n\nAsync function at `core/src/indexer/reorg.rs:136`. Generic over `ChainProvider`. Currently has zero test coverage. This is a critical reorg-safety function.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `core/src/indexer/reorg.rs` (add tests to existing test module)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write tests for the happy path — matching block found**\n\n```rust\nuse crate::provider::mock::MockChainProvider;\nuse crate::indexer::fetch_logs::BlockMeta;\nuse lru::LruCache;\nuse std::num::NonZeroUsize;\n\n#[tokio::test]\nasync fn find_fork_point_matching_block_returns_next() {\n    let hash_a = B256::from([0xAA; 32]);\n    let hash_b = B256::from([0xBB; 32]);\n\n    // Cache has blocks 98 and 99, both with known hashes\n    let mut cache: LruCache<u64, BlockMeta> = LruCache::new(NonZeroUsize::new(64).unwrap());\n    cache.put(98, BlockMeta { hash: hash_a, parent_hash: B256::ZERO, timestamp: 1000 });\n    cache.put(99, BlockMeta { hash: hash_b, parent_hash: hash_a, timestamp: 1012 });\n\n    // Provider returns canonical blocks — block 99 matches, block 98 matches\n    use alloy::consensus::Header;\n    use alloy::rpc::types::Block;\n\n    let canonical_99 = AnyRpcBlock::from(Block {\n        header: Header {\n            number: 99,\n   